SIMPLE: scantling
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scantling
<hw>Scant"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Scant</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>Not plentiful; small;
scanty.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scantling</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scantling
<hw>Scant"ling</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF.
<ets>eschantillon</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧chantillon</ets>, a sample,
pattern, example. In some senses confused with <ets>scant</ets>
insufficient. See <er>Scantle</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A fragment; a bit; a little piece.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>A piece or quantity cut for a special purpose; a sample.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such as exceed not this <qex>scantling</qex>; -- to be solace to
the sovereign and harmless to the people.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A pretty <qex>scantling</qex> of his knowledge may taken by his
deferring to be baptized so many years.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A small quantity; a little bit; not much.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Reducing them to narrow <qex>scantlings</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A piece of timber sawed or cut of a small size, as
for studs, rails, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The dimensions of a piece of timber with regard to
its breadth and thickness; hence, the measure or dimensions of
anything.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A rough draught; a rude sketch or outline.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A frame for casks to lie upon; a trestle.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scantly</ent>⟦br⟧
